worldwide, January 2004--March 2005. MMWR 2005;54:408--12.
2. CDC. Progress toward poliomyelitis eradication---Nigeria, January 2004--
July 2005. MMWR 2005;54:873--7.
3. Liu HM, Zheng DP, Zhang LB, Oberste MS, Pallansch MA, Kew OM. Molecular
evolution of a type 1 wild-vaccine poliovirus recombinant during widespread
circulation in China. J Virol 2000;74:11153--61.
4. CDC. Progress toward poliomyelitis eradication---poliomyelitis outbreak in
Sudan, 2004. MMWR 2005;54:97--9.
5. World Health Organization. Poliomyelitis, Yemen---update. Wkly Epidemiol
Rec 2005;80:194.
6. World Health Organization. Poliomyelitis, Indonesia---update. Wkly
Epidemiol Rec 2005;80:299.
7. World Health Organization. Poliomyelitis, Angola---update. Wkly Epidemiol
Rec 2005;80:298.
8. World Health Organization. WHO vaccine preventable diseases monitoring
system: 2005 global summary. Geneva, Switzerland: World Health Organization;
2005. Available at <http://www.who.int/vaccines-
documents/globalsummary/globalsummary.pdf >.
9. Caceres VM, Sutter RW. Sabin monovalent oral polio vaccines: review of past
experiences and their potential use after polio eradication. Clin Infect Dis
2001;33:531--41.
10. World Health Organization. Advisory committee on polio eradication---
standing recommendations for responding to circulating polioviruses in polio-
free areas. Wkly Epidemiol Rec 2005;80:330--1.
(A) World Health Assembly. Global eradication of poliomyelitis by the year
2000: resolution of the 41st World Health Assembly. Geneva, Switzerland: World
Health Organization; 1988 (WHA resolution no. 41.28).
(B) As of February 1, 2006, Niger and Egypt were considered no longer endemic
for WPV because neither country had indigenous transmission during the
preceding 12 months.
(C) Countries with no evidence of indigenous WPV transmission for greater than
1 year.
(D) In this report, Niger was not included among the 21 polio-free countries
with imported WPV because Niger was not considered polio-free at the beginning
of 2005.
(E) The sequence of the complete VP1 coding region is determined by using
automated cycle-sequencing procedures described previously (3) and by
comparing the resulting sequences with those in a database of all recent
poliovirus isolates. The origins and routes of virus importation are then
derived from phylogenetic analysis.
(F) Imported virus resulted in 48 cases from 3 importations in Chad;
transmission of older endemic lineages of WPV type 3 accounted for 2 cases.
(G) Imported virus resulted in 146 cases in Sudan; transmission of nonimported
endemic lineages of WPV type 1 accounted for 5 other cases and WPV type 3 for
three cases.
(H) For the purposes of this analysis, transmission after importation of WPV
type 1 was considered to have stopped if countries did not detect WPV during
the preceding 6 months.
(I) SIAs consist of 1) national immunization days (NIDs), nationwide mass
campaigns conducted during a short period (i.e., days to weeks) during which a
dose of OPV is administered to all children (usually aged less than 5 years)
regardless of previous vaccination history; 2) sub-NIDs (SNIDs), which are
campaigns similar to NIDs but confined to certain parts of the country; or 3)
mopping-up intensive focal campaigns focusing on high-risk areas after
poliovirus isolation in countries that are endemic for WPV.
(J) mOPV1 has greater immunogenicity for WPV type 1 per dose than trivalent
OPV (9).
(K) Continuing with at least 2 NID rounds after the last virus is detected.
