[The above review is a nice summary of the status of wild poliovirus
circulation during the period 2002-2005. For the most up-to-date data on
poliomyelitis, check the polioeradication website, which includes cases as of
14 Feb 2006.�
<http://www.polioeradication.org/casecount.asp>
The data support the recommendations for the need to keep OPV coverage levels
of the population at or above 80 percent as a protective means against
reintroduction with continued circulation of the WPV.
A pity there wasn't inclusion of information on the vaccine-derived poliovirus
(VDPV) type 1 that has been circulating in Indonesia. According to the WHO
Regional Office for South-East Asia website, there have been 45 cases of VDPV
type 1 identified in Madura island in East Java Province.�
<http://w3.whosea.org/vaccine/linkfiles/polioupdate.pdf>
These cases have continued to mount -- see Poliomyelitis - Worldwide (Somalia,
Ethiopia, Indonesia) 20060111.0103 -- and are still "under investigation."
Information on the derivation of these VDPVs, especially if they are
genetically linked to the recent use of mOPV, is of interest. It is the
largest outbreak of poliomyelitis associated with VDPV identified to date. -
Mod.MPP]
